Hello! I'm Luna. As a UI/UX designer, I believe that even the smallest elements, like a primary button, should feel intentional, accessible, and delightful to interact with. 

A great primary button needs strong visual hierarchy, smooth micro-interactions, and strict adherence to accessibility standards (like touch-target sizing and keyboard focus states).

Here is a complete, modern, and production-ready CSS implementation for a primary button.

### The HTML
Keep your markup semantic and clean. Using `<button>` is always preferred over `<a>` for actions.

```html
<button class="btn-primary">
  <!-- Optional: Icon can go here -->
  Get Started
</button>

<button class="btn-primary" disabled>
  Processing...
</button>
```

### The CSS
I'm using CSS custom properties (variables) to make this highly maintainable and easy to theme. 

```css
/* 1. Define your design tokens (variables) */
:root {
  --btn-primary-bg: #4F46E5;       /* Modern Indigo */
  --btn-primary-bg-hover: #4338CA; /* Darker on hover */
  --btn-primary-bg-active: #3730A3;/* Darkest on click */
  --btn-primary-text: #FFFFFF;

  --btn-shadow: 0 1px 2px 0 rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
  --btn-shadow-hover: 0 4px 6px -1px rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.2), 0 2px 4px -1px rgba(79, 70, 229, 0.1);

  --btn-radius: 0.5rem;            /* 8px - soft but professional */
  --btn-transition: all 0.2s cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1);
}

/* 2. Base Button Styles */
.btn-primary {
  /* Layout & Sizing */
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: center;
  gap: 0.5rem; /* Space for icons if added */

  /* 
   * UX Note: Padding ensures a minimum touch target of 44x44px 
   * on mobile devices, meeting WCAG accessibility guidelines.
   */
  padding: 0.75rem 1.5rem; 
  min-height: 2.75rem; 

  /* Typography */
  font-family: inherit;
  font-size: 1rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  line-height: 1.5;
  letter-spacing: 0.01em;
  text-decoration: none;
  white-space: nowrap;

  /* Visuals */
  color: var(--btn-primary-text);
  background-color: var(--btn-primary-bg);
  border: none;
  border-radius: var(--btn-radius);
  box-shadow: var(--btn-shadow);

  /* Interaction */
  cursor: pointer;
  transition: var(--btn-transition);
  user-select: none;
  -webkit-tap-highlight-color: transparent; /* Removes mobile tap flash */
}

/* 3. Interactive States */

/* Hover: Lift slightly and deepen color */
.btn-primary:hover:not(:disabled) {
  background-color: var(--btn-primary-bg-hover);
  box-shadow: var(--btn-shadow-hover);
  transform: translateY(-1px);
}

/* Active/Click: Push down for tactile feedback */
.btn-primary:active:not(:disabled) {
  background-color: var(--btn-primary-bg-active);
  box-shadow: var(--btn-shadow);
  transform: translateY(0px);
}

/* Focus: High-contrast ring for keyboard navigation (Accessibility) */
.btn-primary:focus-visible {
  outline: 2px solid var(--btn-primary-bg);
  outline-offset: 2px;
}

/* Remove default outline for mouse users */
.btn-primary:focus:not(:focus-visible) {
  outline: none;
}

/* Disabled: Clear visual indication of inactivity */
.btn-primary:disabled {
  opacity: 0.5;
  cursor: not-allowed;
  box-shadow: none;
  transform: none;
}
```

### 🎨 Luna's UX/UI Design Breakdown:

1. **`inline-flex` with `gap`**: Using flexbox instead of block/inline-block ensures that if you ever add an SVG icon next to your text, it will align perfectly without needing extra margin hacks.
2. **Micro-interactions (`transform`)**: The subtle `translateY(-1px)` on hover and reset on active creates a physical, "tactile" feel. It makes the UI feel responsive and premium.
3. **`focus-visible` vs `focus`**: We use `:focus-visible` to show the accessibility ring *only* when the user is navigating via keyboard (Tab key). Mouse users won't see the annoying blue outline when clicking, but keyboard users retain full accessibility.
4. **Cubic Bezier Easing**: `cubic-bezier(0.4, 0, 0.2, 1)` is a standard material-style easing curve. It makes the hover transition feel natural and snappy, rather than linear and robotic.
5. **Theming**: By using CSS variables in `:root`, you can easily implement Dark Mode later by simply redefining the variables inside a `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` query.

### Actionable Next Steps:
* **Add an Icon:** Drop an inline SVG inside the `<button>` tag before the text. The `gap: 0.5rem` in the CSS will handle the spacing automatically.
* **Create Variants:** Duplicate the class to make `.btn-secondary` (transparent background, colored border) or `.btn-ghost` (transparent background, colored text) by simply swapping the CSS variables! 

Let me know if you'd like me to design the secondary/ghost variants or a loading spinner state to go with this!
